	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.85]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>As a person who has at times worked in the game software industry, I can see both sides to this.&nbsp;&nbsp;There is a certain challenge to beating mobs outside of the designer's intended approach.  That really does make you SMARTER than the designer and more DILIGENT than they are at figuring out how their own game works.<br><br>But there is also the issue that no game can be designed to withstand the full intent for 400,000 people to bend the game over and to intentionally break the design and implementation of the game.<br><br>Hackers play the same game with viruses, worms, trojan horses, etc.  They desire to impact the world around them in a BIG way that 'cheats' on how life is supposed to work.  In some ways, their 'cheat' is no worse than a movie star, baseball player, or music artist.  Those with unusual talents often feel they should be seen as being at a distance from the rest of the world.<br><br>But in the final analysis, this item is an act of petty vindication by the designers.  It strikes me as humorous and therefore somewhat more innoculous than, say, a pit trap or a shotgun that fires when you open the rear door, but it remains primarily a bald-faced statement of Verant's vindictiveness towards customers that pay them to play their game.<br><br>That does not excuse the people who exploit the game.  Their behavior is just as atrocious.  Every person has a sense of where the lines of decency lie, and when someone chooses to cross them, they literally deserve anything that they get in return, even a shotgun blast in the face from an illegal mantrap.  They deserve it, but it is still wrong.<br><br>Saeul<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Wed Nov 13 20:07:35 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
